Chet,<br><br>
You raise a very important subject. I agree with you that how we feel about ouselves is a very critical part in our recovery.<br><br>
As I have posted before, I hung my decorations out in public view in my office some months ago. I did that for myself. I have forgotten how many times those frames were carried in and out of the door in a bag, should I, why bother, what will people say, how will they react, are there people out there who still believed in the tag of baby killers? ...... I was scared.<br><br>
It finally sunk in one day that I was really proud of what those decorations ment. They ment that I did my job to the best of my abilities and that was acknowledged. They were also given to me back then by people in country in whom I had great respect. Why shouldn't I be proud of them?<br><br>
Well, I took the plunge one day, and put them up, and cringed for a while at the confused glances. After a while, a few ventured that they really did not know what they ment.<br>
All I offered was that I did my job really well. They understood. Someday, they may ask more, and I may be ready to say more. But for now, whenever I look at that wall, I feel really proud, inside, where it really matters.<br><br>
I still get twinges now and then, some of the old feelings, but they stay up on the wall in full view where they belong. My Grandfather was proud of me and the decorations, too. I guess that makes two!
